Hands-on — diagnosing skew on the bank's silver build.

This walkthrough makes skew visible. It constructs a deliberately skewed dataset — a big side of several million transactions where most rows belong to one corporate customer, joined against a small per-customer attribute table where that corporate customer is just a single row.

Then it runs the join twice. First with adaptive execution turned off, so you can see the un-handled skew pattern — one straggler task running far longer than the rest, the classic max-far-above-median signature. Then it turns on adaptive skew-join handling and re-measures, and you watch that straggler get split and the stage finish much faster.

The point is to see, on one concrete example, both the symptom in the timing and the fix in action — so run it on a databricks cluster, or locally, on a recent runtime that supports skew-join handling.
